hagáin</b> was a learned family in Connacht. See also   Keegan  ."]},{"name":"Mackey","meanings":["Pronounced with the stress on the first syllable, this is Irish, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Macdha</b> ‘descendant of <i>Macdha</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘virile, manly’.","With the stress on the second syllable, it is a variant of Scottish and Irish   McKay  ."]},{"name":"Quay","meanings":["Scottish and Irish: shortened form of   McKay   or   McKee  .","English: variant of   Kay  .","French: topographic name for someone who lived in a house on a quayside, from Old French <i>quai</i> ‘quay’."]},{"name":"McKee","meanings":["Irish (northern): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Aodha</b> or <b>Mac Aoidh</b> ‘son of <i>Aodh</i>’, an old personal name meaning ‘fire’. Thus, this name has the same origin as   McKay  ,   McGee  ,   McCoy  , and   McHugh  ."]},{"name":"Mackay","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   McKay  ."]},{"name":"McHugh","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Conal, Sinead, Brigid, Conall, Cormac, Eamon, Eamonn, Fintan, Kieran, Malachy, Patrick Sean.","Irish and Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Aodha</b> or <b>Mac Aoidh</b> ‘son of <i>Aodh</i>’, an old personal name meaning ‘fire’, originally the name of a pagan god. Thus the name has the same origin as   McKay  ,   McGee  , and   McCoy  . See also   Hughes   3."]}]},{"name":"Macheth","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish:  see  McBeth  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McBeth","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Beatha</b> ‘son of life’, i.e. ‘man of religion’, used as a personal name. Compare Irish   McVey   and   McAbee  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Macheth McKay was born about 1112. She had at least 1 son with Flemming Freskin de Moray."},"et":{"ABT 1112–":"umbes 1112–Surnud","1107–1172":"1107–1172","1138–1203":"1138–1203","1112–Female":"1112–Surnud","1107":"1107","1138":"1138","1203